      • PROPERTY_DELIMITER

        public static final String PROPERTY_DELIMITER
        Default property delimiter, used to construct property path expressions. Typically an expression on the form anObject.foo.bar.baz implies that a set of JavaBean getters should be invoked on the anObject object.
        See Also:
        FIND_JAVABEAN_GETTERS, getProperty(Object, String), Constant Field Values

      • SORTED_CLASS_SUPPLIER

        public static final Supplier<SortedSet<Class<?>>> SORTED_CLASS_SUPPLIER

        Standard Supplied to create a SortedSet of Class'es using the CLASSNAME_COMPARATOR to determine order within the SortedSet yielded. The typical application of this Supplier is

         
     [someStream].collect(Collectors.toCollection(TypeAlgorithms.SORTED_CLASS_SUPPLIER));

      • SORTED_CLASSNAME_COLLECTOR

      • FIND_PUBLIC_METHODS

        public static final Function<Class<?>,SortedSet<Method>> FIND_PUBLIC_METHODS
        Function returning all public methods (including those inherited from superclasses) within a given class. The sort order of the returned SortedSet is given by MEMBER_COMPARATOR.

      • FIND_JAVABEAN_GETTERS

        public static final Function<Class<?>,SortedMap<String,Method>> FIND_JAVABEAN_GETTERS
        Function retrieving a SortedSet relating readable JavaBean property (names) to their corresponding getter Methods. The JavaBean getter methods within the Object class (i.e. "getClass()" will be ignored).

      • getProperty

        public static Object getProperty(@NotNull
                                 Object pointOfOrigin,
                                 @NotNull
                                 String propertyExpression)
                          throws IllegalArgumentException

        Retrieves a property from the supplied pointOfOrigin Object using the supplied propertyExpression as the definition of a property path. The property path should be on the form foo.bar.baz providing the JavaBean property names ("foo", "bar" and "baz"). Such JavaBean property names do - in turn - imply methods with the signature getFoo(), getBar() and getBaz() respectively.

        The code above should yield an implementation chain similar to the following:

             
         // The call:
         final SomeType result = TypeAlgorithms.getProperty(pointOfOrigin, "foo.bar.baz");

         // ... is equal to calling the JavaBean getter methods in the
         // order given within the propertyExpression:
         final SomeType result = pointOfOrigin.getFoo().getBar().getBaz();
        Parameters:
        pointOfOrigin - The object in which we should start the JavaBean invocation chain.
        propertyExpression - The property expression defining a chained
        Returns:
        The result of the
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if a JavaBean getter method is not present within the current/intermediary type in which it was requested to be invoked.
